turn a default value. It seems like it could be a good fail-safe option. I’m not entirely sure what the default should be or if it’s the best approach overall. Maybe I should dig deeper into the potential outcomes of returning a default versus handling errors directly. It's interesting to think about how it might impact user experience. Let’s explore this further!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test class loading**\\n\\nI’m thinking about loading a test class at build time using its name, which should be supported by generated metadata. But does it really need to be open-ended? It’s a known class name in the test constant, and the agent will capture it, so that could be okay. However, the public API needs some reflection. I could add an ErrorHandler property to the target, which would replace Level conversion coverage with a different conversion path in PropertySetter, so I’ll need to implement the ErrorHandler interface. I should inspect that interface further.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_oyiunalRcA4bHCegdhqQUu3y|fc_0d8c5ba1daecb9c8016a0104237b648195b3c1d6d053f04258", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge1/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.logging.log4j/log4j-1.2-api/2.18.0/main/extracted/org/apache/log4j/spi/ErrorHandler.java", "limit": 200}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1738, "output": 1426, "cacheRead": 39424, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 42588, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778451471073, "responseId": "resp_0d8c5ba1daecb9c8016a01040fc1148195aba762a7c1182af6"}}
